name: 2-amino-5-nitrobenzonitrile
Reason: The structure of 2-amino-5-nitrobenzonitrile consists of a benzene ring as the basic unit, an amino group (-NH2), a nitro group (-NO2), and a nitrile group (-C#N). The benzene ring has a significant effect on the melting point due to strong π-π stacking interactions between aromatic rings. As a reference, benzene itself has a melting point of 5.5°C. Each substituent will affect the melting point differently based on its own properties. The amino group is slightly electron-donating and can engage in hydrogen bonding, which typically increases the melting point. The nitro group is a strong electron-withdrawing group and introduces intermolecular dipole-dipole interactions, significantly raising the melting point. The nitrile group, being linear and polar, will also increase the melting point due to dipole-dipole interactions and its impact on the molecular geometry, which can promote more orderly packing in the solid state. The effects of the functional groups can be estimated as follows: amino group: +20°C due to hydrogen bonding potential; nitro group: +80°C due to strong electron-withdrawing nature and dipole-dipole interactions; nitrile group: +30°C due to linearity and polarity aiding in crystal packing. The sum of these effects added to the base melting point of benzene gives the predicted melting point.
